commit_message:
Add OS::Ironic::Chassis resource

Adds initial support for Ironic (in contrib), with one resource
which exposes the chassis API.

Change-Id: I9932637dceca6e33565754a5723b44365cae159c
blueprint: ironic-resource

By the way, why would you want to do it at all? I mean support using Ironic w/o Nova here?'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-08-12 06:25:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I am -1 on the series of all four patches, and would really like to understand what the intent here is... Please explain in what situation Heat should create resources in Ironic.


While trying not to sound like I'm ranting, it is quite late, so apologies if this sounds rant-ish. Here are a few of my objections to heat having *anything* to do with Ironic....

Heat should not duplicate a large set of functions that Nova provides, which is what would be required to provision instances in ironic directly. Instead, Heat should talk to Nova when provisioning bare metal instances with Ironic (which it can alraedy do just fine).

Ironic's API is admin-only. There is *no* user-facing API. Heat, AIUI, acts on behalf of an end-user, not an operator.

The creation or deletion of Ironic resources represent PHYSICAL actions by an operator (eg, adding a new server to the data center). These are not virtual resources to be created/deleted on demand by users.

Thanks,
Devananda"}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2014-08-15 07:20:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Add Ironic resource base class

Adds initial support for Ironic (in contrib), a base and client class
to be used by ironic resource plugins.

blueprint: ironic-resource
Change-Id: I032824d92232aea1e02d7488951547dc677a92ac

Steven, could you please hard-wrap it? It's very hard to read it directly on Gerrit."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-11 13:28:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 13:52:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/78/120778/3/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/44cf336 : FAILURE in 35s'}, {'account_id': 114, 'date': '2014-09-11 13:56:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:06:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:27:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:29:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> So is there something for Heat to manage here beyond the initial deployment?

atm I'm assuming probably not - once the initial configuration is complete, we probably have to move on and surrender the nodes to Ironic/Nova forever.

That said, update may offer some interesting future possibilities, if it were possible for example to orchestrate decommissioning a node, modifying it (firmware update, reconfigure for a different role or whatever) then putting it back in the pool of available nodes."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:46:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/78/120778/5/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/ee3f7bf/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 02s'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-12 14:08:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I'll attempt to outline my objections to this here, but we may need to take it to the ML.

- many of the functions you describe add the intended use of these templates (eg, firmware update, build raid, change bios) are not available via Ironics standard API. They _may_ be available in one or more vendor extensions, but the API may (and will) vary between vendors, until such time as these interfaces are promoted to standard or core interfaces in ironic.

- he discovery has been contentious"}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-12 14:41:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Urg, that posted before I was done.

- HW discovery had been contentious lately; we'll revisit it in Paris, but I suspect the outcome will be a wide agreement that discovery is out of scope for the current project, and we should anticipate interaction with site-local inventory management systems

- you wouldn't decommission a node to change its HW configuration - if deleted from ironic, you'd have no direct means to update bios,raid, etc through ironic. You might put it in maintenance mode, to hide it from nova temporarily while changing configuration, though this isn't a workflow ironic intentionally supports today. (This may be a semantic nit with the spec)

- I believe the intended plan, at least for TripleO, was to push flavor metadata just-in-time down to ironic to reconfigure a node if/when it changes roles. This spec is taking a different angle, and while I don't object, I'd like to see a discussion of pros/cons vs the previously discussed approach

- this question could be the result of a lack of understanding heat on my part, but AFAIK you're going to have difficulty expressing "change $properties on resource $type to $newpropertirs" because ironic does not provide a way to search for nodes by type. You either know the nodes UUID, or a nova instance UUID, or a MAC address of the node - there is no other way to uniquely identify a node. The heat template would need to contain the node UUID, which is usually generated when the node is first enrolled. (You can precreate the UUID, but it must be a real UUID, not a name)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:22:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

>  The heat template would need to contain the node UUID, which is usually 

Heat would store that UUID in the resource table of our DB, same as we do for all resources, I don't think it would need to be specified in the template (but it would need to be included in the adopt data if we went for the possible post-discovery workflow I mention.

Ultimately the first step in trying any of this stuff out is basic Heat->Ironic interoperability.  Contrib resoures are disabled by default, so IMO it's not really relevant if this is a niche use-case or even a dead-end, it's just an experimental feature which some of us would like to try out, and I've now justified, in detail, why.

I think the big picture discussion will be worthwhile and helpful, I'd rather not superimpose that entire discussion on this spec - I'm just trying to justify the tiniest of steps in the direction outlined, not validate the entire vision by writing these extremely simple resources."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-12 16:48:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@shardy, Thanks for clarifying how heat stores the resource UUID.


At the end of the spec is this line:

  it may not be an obviously-useful feature until some of the related
  drac integration lands in Ironic, as well as completing autodiscovery and
  figuring out the adopt/update-converge and node tagging steps mentioned above. 

Some of the points I brought up are in relation to this. 

(a) autodiscovery may be deemed out-of-scope and so never land 

(b) drac-specific or ilo-specific management features are not part of Ironic's standard API, they're presently both vendor extensions with no direct support in our python client. If the primary use-case of adding these resource classes to Heat is to interact with an optional, non-discoverable extension, then I think my questioning of this work's timeliness is valid.

If this spec is intended to outline an in-tree proof of concept, and that is the preferred approach for doing a POC in Heat, then that's fine and great. FWIW, I don't like in-tree POC code, and I'm happy to explain why if anyone is interested, but that's a minor process thing, not related to technical issues or scope.

To rephrase -- I think that this spec is a good place to "clarify the use-case and figure out what's missing", which is precisely why I'm commenting on it and trying to learn more about Heat's internals. I'm not trying to block the work, but help align it with Ironic's current status and future goals. Apologies if my prior comments came across differently.

-Devananda'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-12 22:10:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Devananda: thanks for the constructive feedback

> (a) autodiscovery may be deemed out-of-scope and so never land

Ok, this is interesting, I've not been following the autodiscovery discussions closely, but *something* has to register the nodes in ironic, right?  So exploring leveraging Heat as a way (not *the* way) to do that seems relatively sane, even if autodiscovery is something Ironic itself doesn't get directly involved in?

> (b) drac-specific or ilo-specific management features are not part of Ironic's standard API

Ok, so I confess I've not yet looked into the interfaces in detail, but my assumption was that we'd need to use the node vendor_passthrough interface, which is a documented part of the Ironic API, is that incorrect?

I accept that the content of what is passed to the API may be vendor specific, but that's one of the interesting advantages of using heat - we can probably encapsulate the vendor specific stuff in provider resources (heat templates), while keeping the resource plugins clean and simple, then folks can very easily substitute whatever vendor specific stuff they want by swapping out heat templates, or at least that's what I've been thinking may be possible.

> If this spec is intended to outline an in-tree proof of concept...

The whole vision described for ready-state is very much in the proof-of-concept phase, but the existence of some simple in-tree resource plugins, while facilitating that, is not really a proof-of-concept in and of themselves - the Ironic API will still exist regardless of the success of the ready-state work, maintaining them in heat is low-overhead (much lower than keeping them out-of-tree), and it's zero overhead to Ironic.

> I think that this spec is a good place to "clarify the use-case and figure out what's missing"

Yup, the constructive discussion is appreciated, and I'm still trying to figure out many details related to the use-case and Ironic.  I just don't want to design the whole car here when what I'm proposing is a the spark-plug ;)

Perhaps I can turn the tables and ask you a question.  Given the use-case detail provided, how would you do it?  E.g if you need a TripleO undercloud to somehow discover 1000 hardware nodes, get them configured (BIOS, RAID, firmware etc as outlined) for various roles, registered with Ironic, and made available to Nova readt to build an overcloud?

I'm interested in your suggestions as perhaps there's a more obvious way to do it I'm missing (given the constraints that it must be portable/reusable and automated)'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-12 23:07:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

>> (a) autodiscovery may be deemed out-of-scope and so never land
> *something* has to register the nodes in ironic, right? 

Yes - generally, we assume it's going to be either a user (at small / POC scale) or more likely something which interfaces between an existing intenvory mgmt system (a CMDB) and Ironic.

> exploring leveraging Heat as a way (not *the* way) to do that seems relatively sane

Possibly? Again, my lack of knowledge of Heat may be coloring my opinion here. Let's assume that anyone operating this at scale *already* has an inventory database which is outside of OpenStack. They want to enroll all those nodes with Ironic, and probably need to do some bidirectional syncing over time (eg, as they both add and decommission nodes).

Is Heat providing a generic enough tool for that? 

>> (b) drac-specific or ilo-specific management features are not part of Ironic's standard API
> my assumption was that we'd need to use the node vendor_passthrough interface
> which is a documented part of the Ironic API, is that incorrect?

Using Ironic's API, you can discover: (a) what drivers are available, (b) what driver a given Node is using, (c) what parameters that driver expects in the node.driver_info resource, (d) whether the driver believes the Node is properly configured (all required parameters present).

You can POST to /v1/nodes/{UUID}/vendor_passthru?method={METHOD}

but you can not GET from this endpoint, and you can not discover what the list of available methods are. These must be published by the vendor (eg, in documentation). Ironic (the project) makes no guarantees regarding this API endpoint.

> folks can very easily substitute whatever vendor specific stuff they want by swapping out heat templates

Cool - so this may be really helpful.

Also, the goal of the /vendor_passthru/ API is specifically to allow vendors to do things *not* yet part of Ironic's standard API, and then, over time, converge them upon a standard which we promote to become part of the standard API.

I think that would be a much better time to create Heat resources / templates -- once there is a standard API for them.

> Perhaps I can turn the tables and ask you a question. Given the use-case detail provided, how would you do it? E.g if you need a TripleO undercloud to somehow discover 1000 hardware nodes, get them configured (BIOS, RAID, firmware etc as outlined) for various roles, registered with Ironic, and made available to Nova readt to build an overcloud?

Autodiscovery aside, I do not disagree with the technical path being proposed here -- if I were going to use Heat to prepare hardware for ready-state, it might be something like what you're describing. At least I don't think it would be radically different.

However, I actually fundamentally don't think Heat is the right tool for this, but again, perhaps I lack the understanding of Heat, or perhaps Heat's scope has expanded. Ironic's resources are not directly related to a cloud application at all, which is why it does not have a user-facing API. Borrowing from Heat's wiki:

  A Heat template describes the infrastructure for a cloud application

  [Heat] .. implements an orchestration engine to launch multiple composite cloud applications 

Neither of these are served by modelling Ironic's primitives.

Adding Ironic's primitives to Heat moves it into the realm of managing resources which are not part of any cloud application. It's like asking Cinder for a storage volume vs. configuring the SAN itself. Heat clearly does the former; it does not, afaik, do the latter."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-13 07:31:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Devananda: again, thanks for the feedback

> Let's assume that anyone operating this at scale *already* has an inventory database which is outside of OpenStack. 

This is a false assumption IMO/IME.  I've worked in plenty of medium scale datacentres where they only tracked the assets and did not maintain a detailed inventory of every box including details required by Ironic, e.g mac addresses.  Autodiscovery (not necessarily via any Ironic feature) makes much more sense in such a situation.

> They want to enroll all those nodes with Ironic, and probably need to do some bidirectional syncing over time (eg, as they both add and decommission nodes).

Heat is quite a good tool for aligning such a manfiest with required state, although I admit it's a somewhat novel/innovative use-case.

> Is Heat providing a generic enough tool for that?

IMO yes, although as acknowledged above, I can see why it's seen as a slightly odd use-case.

Think about what you need to do - take a manifest of hardware details (a document of some sort), and translate that into API calls to Ironic.  Converting text documents into API calls is what Heat does.  (Ok there will invariably be some document format mangling somewhere outside heat)

> You can POST to /v1/nodes/{UUID}/vendor_passthru?method={METHOD} but you can not GET from this endpoint, and you can not discover what the list of available methods are. 

I think for this limited use-case (e.g in the TripleO undercloud where the variables are considerably limited compared to a typical public cloud scenario, that is sufficient for the time being.


> I think that would be a much better time to create Heat resources / templates -- once there is a standard API for them.

I think not doing a PoC because there may, possibly, be some slightly optimized interface available in the future is counter productive.  If Ironic provides vendor neutral interfaces for this stuff in a future release, great!  We'll refactor some templates and remove a bunch of maintenance overhead by simplifying them, but waiting a year to even try the idea out to see if it works seems like a waste of valuable time to me (given that we're trying to build something which works *now*, then polish it later)

> Autodiscovery aside, I do not disagree with the technical path being proposed here

That is good to hear, particularly given your initial (strongly negative) feedback on the code reviews.

> However, I actually fundamentally don't think Heat is the right tool for this, 

If Ironic provided vendor agnostic ways to specify all this stuff, and somehow magically prepared hardware to a known state for a particular role (e.g via nova flavors or whatever), then I'd agree with you.  But it doesn't do any of that yet, so this is an interim workaround while that is incrementally added, as you alluded to earlier.

> Ironic's resources are not directly related to a cloud application at all, which is why it does not have a user-facing API.

I think what you need to keep in mind here, is we're not talking about a generic cloud application - we're talking about the TripleO undercloud, which is itself a novel innovative and, lets face it, slightly weird use case for Heat.

The stated goal of TripleO is to deploy OpenStack using only OpenStack tools, and that necessarily requires driving nails in with the wrong type of hammer from time to time.  Given that Heat is the hammer used for everything in TripleO, it makes sense to leverage it to solve this use case, or at least try to - there are no new tools to integrate or write an maintain, we just need to connect two tools already in use.

> Adding Ironic's primitives to Heat moves it into the realm of managing resources which are not part of any cloud application. It's like asking Cinder for a storage volume vs. configuring the SAN itself.

Ironic nodes are part of a cloud application, you just currently support a relatively limited model for user-specified optimization of those resources.

If Ironic (via nova flavors or whatever) allowed us to say "baremetal, optimzed for VM hypervisor)" and it magically did all the stuff described in the spec, we wouldn't need any of this ready state stuff at all.  In the future, when it does, we just delete a bunch of stuff from some templates and switch to the shiny-optimized way.

Treating deploying a fully optimized OpenStack cloud as deploying an application via Heat (which is what TripleO does) is initially a hard thing to wrap your head around (it's certainly taken me a while!) - it's a hugely ambitious (terrifying?) undertaking, and it invariably exposes feature gaps all over the place, I'm just exploring some immediately achievable steps which might close one of them - I'm more than happy to be given a better hammer at some future point :)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-13 07:46:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I'm not actually certain where the "ready state" vision originated, but Rob Hirschfeld has written about it so maybe it was him:

http://robhirschfeld.com/2014/04/25/ready-state-infrastructure/

http://robhirschfeld.com/tag/ready-state/

I'll add him to the review, perhaps he can provide feedback as to the accuracy of my interpretation of the ready-state vision applied to TripleO/Ironic/Heat.

Maybe I should add a link to his blog in the spec for additional context, if folks would find that helpful?'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-14 19:12:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@shardy,

I think this is a great discussion, but I feel that we've long ago passed the depth and detail of discussion where this ought to be on the mailing list. It's also getting hard to track and reply to each point in gerrit's UI -- I found myself drafting a reply in gmail just to paste it here last time, which is clearly an indication we should just move this to email :)

Would you mind starting a thread on this, summarizing your points, and I'll respond by summarizing mine? We can then take it from there. Even if we do not agree, I think putting the discussion out there ahead of the summit is worthwhile -- I could see this becoming a topic in Heat's track.

Regards,
Devananda"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-15 07:29:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Devananda:

> ... this ought to be on the mailing list. 

Sure, I'm happy to start a thread summarising the discussions to date.

> I could see this becoming a topic in Heat's track.

To be honest, I think we've long past the point where I've provided adequate justification for the Heat aspects of this (e.g the spec we've been debating here).  

I think getting some basic resources in the heat contrib tree is relatively uncontentious (the only person objecting to them is you, and the BP was approved by the Heat PTL some time ago).

So I don't see a topic on the Heat track as appropriate really.  

However a "ready state" topic spanning the broader discussion captured here, e.g if the overall idea has legs, may be appropriate, I think this falls into the TripleO track though, as it's about TripleO deployment workflow.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-15 13:23:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

ML thread started:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/045985.html'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-09-26 02:41:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

It seems weird to me that we have to put resources into contrib just because they are for admin only. I mean really can't we attach policies to resources? Like "resource X requires admin/or role X" and is not visible to any one else? The nova flavor is another example of this.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-02 13:22:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> It seems weird to me that we have to put resources into contrib just because they are for admin only...

I guess, I think historically though we've taken the view that admin-only is bad mkay, and also that "admin" is poorly defined ref keystone bug #968696.

Also we'd need a stuff like resource-type-list and template validation to be conext dependent based on roles, where we have no visibility at runtime of what roles are actually required by the remote service, so we'd end up with hard-coded assumptions based on service policy.json defaults.  

Really, there needs to be a centralized policy repository for all endpoints which we can query (or a way to query policy on an endpoint directly), so each resource could register the API actions it expects to use, then we can query and get a list of required roles at validation time.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-07 08:30:43.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Alrighty, Devananda has blocked this work at every turn, without giving any clear vision of how to solve the actual problem.  

A pretty unproductive escapade all in all, really, and not a particularly impressive example of either review etiquette or the community working together to solve a problem.

Nobody else is stepping up to oppose the impressively negative and opinionated review feedback, so I guess there's nothing left to do but abandon this and consider other approaches."}]

commit_message:
Spec for Ironic Heat (contrib) resources

An initial spec for the proposed Ironic resources, attempting to
clarify the use-case and figure out what's missing to enable the
ready-state work which they aim to enable.

Co-Authored-By: Victor Lowther <Victor_Lowther@dell.com>
Co-Authored-By: Angus Thomas <athomas@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Rename 'slave' to 'replica'

Remove all references to the terms 'slave' and 'master, except in code
that is specific to MySQL. Use the terms 'replica' and 'replication
source' instead.

Add a db migration to rename the instances.slave_of_id column to
replica_of_id.

Update apischema.py to reflect support for replicas.

Co-Authored-By: Doug Shelley <doug@parelastic.com>
Depends-On: Id22d18a84a4ac104ff8af09959e8eb2ae0102e97
Closes-Bug: 1373668

Change-Id: I68f6c5f2fdb210afcbad504df4cf0588400fc42a

commit_message:
Fix unsafe SSL connection on TrustedFilter

TrustedFilter was using httplib which doesn't check for CAs.
Here the change is using Requests and verifies local CAs by default (or another
one if provided)
This effort is related to CVE 2013-2255.

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1373993

Change-Id: I0b8e6319a4cc39876b1e396ef705f0fc5def1e44

commit_message:
Update the Elastic Data Processing (EDP) documentation page

* Add description of MapReduce.Streaming job type
* Add description of Spark job type
* Add reference to advanced configuration for Swfit proxy
* Note that .sahara suffix is added to Swift URLs automatically
* A few minor changes

Closes-Bug: 1374574
Closes-Bug: 1374606
Change-Id: Ie53888975ce436439cc808b2fdc45dff66bae1a9
(cherry picked from commit 7973db35e61b0c2d686798cb2de50d281713b03b)

commit_message:
Fixed volumes configuration in spark plugin

Only current node group config should influence on data location.

Change-Id: Id1d6f7bf29fd5b8d7734d3358b6e34f06bf084da

commit_message:
Fixed cinder check for non-admin user

It could happen that user doesn't have privileges to perform
list_services. Sahara should use admin user for that.

Refactored keystone client creation to give admin user
access to keystone via API v2.

Change-Id: I275fa07a02f4729f2fc20fcd1f0ea65f3c4d50b2
Closes-Bug: #1375806
Closes-Bug: #1376336
(cherry picked from commit 46ab3f5bfe4c19c3fc028158af705ebde595f355)

commit_message:
Mark custom properties in image schema as non-base

Currently it is impossible to determine if given image schema property
is base or custom one and knowledge of that can be handy in some
situations.    Proposed change appends to every custom property special
key which determiness that it is not a base property.

Change-Id: I49255255df311036d516768afc55475c1f9aad47
Partial-Bug: #1371559

commit_message:
Adding support for oslo.rootwrap to namespace access

Changes
* adding configuration options for rootwrap
* refactoring ssh connection to use rootwrap as a proxy when requested
* adding documentation for rootwrap configuration
* adding default rootwrap filters file
* adding default sudoers conf file for sahara user
* adding default rootwrap conf file for sahara-rootwrap
* adding sahara-rootwrap cli script
* adding requirement for oslo.rootwrap

Change-Id: I7871400b2342a4cd1a8910ae5121b1bfdc46078d
Closes-Bug: #1271349
(cherry picked from commit 43785e6e9edc21678fc43f2cf4f7516d19469199)

commit_message:
Add tools/gate/build-images script

It will simplify configuring and tuning for our upcoming images
gating. In gate job we'll just exec this script and it will do
all the things we need. Let's start just with the building all
images for the specified plugin.

Change-Id: Iecef82bec8eb8d10218c5ad2b763ccabb41053ad

commit_message:

repository broke a test in the extract_swift_flags.py script. This patch
changes the test to make the script work again.

commit_message:
Specify the MetadefNamespace.namespace column is not nullable

The metadef_namespaces table definition indicates the namespace
column as not accepting nulls. The related MetadefNamespace ORM class
should also indicate that the namespace column does not accept nulls
with "nullable=False" in the column definition.

Change-Id: I681747b6579a2284f23bf154889a61c639b0616d
Closes-Bug: 1367619

The enum types look good, but the description of the metadata needs to be updated to include information about when it can be used.  Right now, a user could click on it and think that they get it and it is somehow automatically used without additional setup.  However, it requires setting up the trust attestation server.  I suggest updating the namespace description as follows:

Trusted compute pools with Intel Trusted Execution Technology (Intel TXT) support IT compliance by protecting virtualized data centers - private, public, and hybrid clouds against attacks toward hypervisor and BIOS, firmware, and other pre-launch software components. The Nova trust scheduling filter must be enabled and configured with the trust attestation service in order to use this feature.

And updating the property description as follows:

Select to ensure that node has been attested by Intel Trusted Execution Technology (Intel TXT). The Nova trust scheduling filter must be enabled and configured with the trust attestation service in order to use this feature.'}, {'account_id': 12299, 'date': '2014-09-22 06:56:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-22 07:57:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Make compute-trust.json compatible with TrustFilter

Current properties inside compute-trust.json does not match
with how TrustFilter in nova works. JSON provides True/False
boolean values but TrustFilter expects trusted/untrusted/unknown
string values. This patch repairs compute-trust.json to be
compatible with TrustFilter.

Change-Id: I26965a549daf9340621b0f18a1b845b39bac4bd8
Closes-Bug: #1369581

commit_message:
Include Metadata Defs Concepts in Dev Docs

The http://docs.openstack.org/developer/glance/
site currently doesn't include the Juno Metadata
Definitions concepts.  This patch adds
an overview of the concepts to this site.

This provides a synopis of the concepts in:
https://github.com/openstack/glance-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/metadata-schema-catalog.rst

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: 1367432
Related-Bug: 1367908
Related-Bug: 1363615
Related-Bug: 1366286
Related-Bug: 1363383
Change-Id: Iad4d388cbbf2f63fa243d04d35032de0cb0bc1b4

commit_message:
Nova instance config drive Metadata Definition

A nova Juno FFE landed to support setting the
img_config_drive property on images to require images
to be booted with a config drive. The Glance Metadata
Definitions should include this property.

See Nova Blueprint:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/config-drive-image-property

Change-Id: Iffc4d4f00f3677ed1fa41233ef6cfbc5c46d8602
Closes-bug: 1367981

Add missing metadefs for Aggregate Filters

The below spec implemented in Juno added numerous properties
that can be added to Host Aggregates. The Metadata
Definitions catalog should include them.

https://github.com/openstack/nova-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/per-aggregate-filters.rst

tests.

commit_message:
Provide __repr__ for SampleFilter

Implement __repr__ for SamplerFilter, so that when we log it we get a more
useful representation printed to the screen, without having to log each
individual field.

Change-Id: I6b23531daa8541b073d27ea4efcac16af3d6a106

commit_message:
Port extended_ips/extended_ips_mac extension to V2.1

This patch port extended_ips/extended_ips_mac extension to V2.1

There are difference between V2 and V3 server show/index &
server address index API response listed below-

'address' field of V2->V3 API response-
"OS-EXT-IPS:type" -> "type"
"OS-EXT-IPS-MAC:mac_addr" -> "mac_addr"

Reverting those attribute same as V2 to work with V2.1

Closes-Bug: #1368495
Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I44902b0402115d1b6e833975e6c2f020ac5ab7c3

commit_message:
added hautoproxy auto-configuring haproxy

This image configures haproxy to forward connections for all available
kubernetes services.  It is meant to be run alongside other contains in
a kubernetes pod to provide access to "remote" services at a consistent
address so that keystone api endpoints can be configured in a sane
fashion.

Change-Id: Ic923c6a772f1bdf36b97b05a1d04de9e5b841ddd

commit_message:
Make versions list sorted for Vanilla and HDP

Right now the list is not sorted. Probably the versions order in
the list is OS dependent. In my case 2.3.0 came before 1.2.1 in UI,
which is not pretty.

The natural ordering is applied to handle cases like 2.2 < 2.13
(lexicographical order will return that 2.2 > 2.13)

Change-Id: I3a98549ff8a369ea202095e8070f65483e0bd099

- check-tempest-dsvm-f20 http://logs.openstack.org/90/122590/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-f20/4c1819a : SUCCESS in 45m 22s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-09-19 12:41:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Nice work - this will make v2.1 testing a lot easier'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-09-19 15:29:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Continuing to register endpoints for every version is going to wind up being a disaster. We need a better way to do this. Register an unversioned endpoint with keystone and implement version discovery in your client.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-09-19 15:31:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Brant's comment is spot on."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-09-19 15:33:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Also, because the service catalog is stored with the token, this will make every token larger. This is especially a problem if the deployment uses PKI tokens. They get passed around and they're already too big."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-19 15:58:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I noticed this week that we were logging the keystone tokens in the nova-api logs and the service_catalog gets logged in that, so yeah, it's huge already, we shouldn't add more stuff to it.

If the version discovery support is available and the keystone team can help getting that into novaclient it'd be helpful - I feel like there is a lot of 'there are better ways to do this' from the keystone team but there isn't much education on that - if it's all doc'ed somewhere can we be pointed to that?"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-20 02:35:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sorry, I cannot understand Brant's suggestion. Maybe I need to learn more about auto-versions-discovery, are there any official clients(python-***client) for supporting auto-versions-discovery ?
I'd like to get hint from them."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-20 16:51:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Dropping my -1 since it's gonna be hard to do this some better way until we know what that is and how to do it."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-22 00:31:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Brant

I guess your suggestion means

 Register endpoints without version part like:
  - http://%SERVICE_HOST%:8774/v2.0/$(tenant_id)s
  - http://%SERVICE_HOST%:8774/v2.1/$(tenant_id)s
  - http://%SERVICE_HOST%:8774/v3
  + http://%SERVICE_HOST%:8774/v3
 Client should generate endpoints from a version and endpoints which is getting from Keystone

right?

if so, it is difficult to do it now for Nova, because the return of "get version list" API doesn't include URL part of each version and we can customize URL point of versions by /etc/nova/api-paste.ini.

The return of "get version list" API
 $ curl -i 'http://192.168.11.62:8774/' -X GET -H "Accept: application/json" -H "X-Auth-Project-Id: demo" -H "X-Auth-Token: {SHA1}a478a30ec8bdadbdb5b8f98d97bf99ac83a8a1ea"
 [..]
 {"versions": [{"status": "CURRENT", "updated": "2011-01-21T11:33:21Z", "id": "v2.0", "links": [{"href": "http://192.168.11.62:8774/v2/", "rel": "self"}]}, {"status": "EXPERIMENTAL", "updated": "2013-07-23T11:33:21Z", "id": "v2.1", "links": [{"href": "http://192.168.11.62:8774/v2/", "rel": "self"}]}]}

The above "id" in the return shows version IDs and we can use them as URL part of versions if Nova environment is default setting. But we can change URL part of versions on /etc/nova/api-paste.ini and if doing that, we cannot use them as URL parts.

If the problem is increasing endpoints, how about removing current Nova v3 API endpoint?
Nova v3 API has disappeared on Juno cycle and we cannot use it now, so I think we can remove it.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-22 00:35:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-09-22 00:44:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

I think swapping the v3 endpoing for the v2.1 is a reasonable compromise for now. We don't support version discovery yet and I'd rather not hold up v2.1 on it. Also going into the future we're doing API versioning through a client header so won't need any url prefix except for backwards compatibility of v2/v2.1"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-22 01:02:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Are there any lock-step changes needed to tempest for this also (or nova.conf options)?  I know we have a periodic job running on the experimental queue for the v3 API, so I'm assuming that needs to be tweaked.

On the plus side, it sounds like with this change we can remove the v3 shell from python-novaclient?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-22 01:29:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

@Matt

Nice catch, I posted some patches for removing current experimental nova-v3-api-tests from the gate:

* Ie2e10d603e10b0f05ec7767ea41b5fe9aca84ccc
* If63dcdb2d05aa0fab0b6848a1248b6678f1ee9ad'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-09-22 08:24:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

I agreed that swapping V3 for v2.1 is the pragmatic way to go for now.   

Going to full version discovery in the client worries me in terms of backwards compatibility -  if we go down that route we're going to have to do some careful thinking to make sure we don't break the client for existing deployed systems."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-22 14:35:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Ken'ichi,

Are you going to propose another patch to remove this?

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-dev/devstack/tree/lib/tempest#n293

And this?

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/tempest/tree/etc/tempest.conf.sample#n398"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-09-24 14:45:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

The ideal is we register the compute endpoint as http://192.168.11.62:8774 (or, even more ideally, https://192.168.11.62/compute), then the client can query the endpoint, parse the response, figure out whether v2 or v2.1 are supported, and it also knows how to get to them because of the links.

This isn't something that Keystone is going to provide, it's going to have to be supported by the Nova server. We've got code in keystoneclient for doing discovery for the Identity API[1] that could be adapted to the compute API. Jamie Lennox has been working on this, and he might have plans to put this in the nova API, too. He's been working lately on providing a way to translate, for example, a catalog with a v2 compute endpoint to a v2.1 compute endpoint, see add_catalog_discover_hack() in [1].

I think removing the compute v3 endpoint should be in a separate commit. That's something we can all get behind.

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/python-keystoneclient/tree/keystoneclient/discover.py"}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-25 00:35:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Brant

I got your version-discovery idea, I think that is a right direction in long term.
and the *links* of "list versions" API response should work for it.

However, current *links* does not work for it because the one of v2.1 is the same as the one of v2.

 $ curl -i 'http://192.168.11.62:8774/' -X GET -H "Accept: application/json" -H "X-Auth-Project-Id: demo" -H "X-Auth-Token: {SHA1}a478a30ec8bdadbdb5b8f98d97bf99ac83a8a1ea"
 [..]
 {"versions": [
     {
        "status": "CURRENT", "updated": "2011-01-21T11:33:21Z", "id": "v2.0",
        "links": [{"href": "http://192.168.11.62:8774/v2/", "rel": "self"}]
     },
     {
        "status": "EXPERIMENTAL", "updated": "2013-07-23T11:33:21Z", "id": "v2.1",
        "links": [{"href": "http://192.168.11.62:8774/v2/", "rel": "self"}]
     }
 ]}

I'm not sure this is a bug of the API, maybe a bug..
In addition, we need to define the other endpoint name except "compute" because of backwards incompatibility as Phil said.
That means we need to consider novaclient behavior for using v2.1 API if version-discovery is necessary.
I feel now these works is a little overkill just for using v2.1 API.

The separated patches are reasonable, I will do it soon.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-25 00:37:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Matt

Really nice catch, they should be removed.
I will do it with the other commit.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-25 00:52:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-25 00:53:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-09-25 00:55:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add Nova v2.1 API endpoint

In Juno cycle, we started to implement Nova v2.1 API and most part
has been implemented now.
For using/testing the API, this patch adds the endpoint setting to
devstack.

Change-Id: I25557cb2b0a1384ee11d3e1ae7d424828e766e50

commit_message:
Source functions from stackrc

stackrc now requires GITREPO, GITBRANCH, GITDIR and has been
dependent on functions for a while (is_package_installed).  Ensure
we source the required functions file when stackrc is loaded.  Avoids
unexpected issues in grenade where they may or may not have been loaded
depending on the configuration.

Closes-bug: #1377274

Change-Id: I5027cfad07af0de7ff39f424601d6f7ec5dcadae

commit_message:
Add v2-on-v3-api spec

Note that this change includes an addition to the doc
index which is needed to bootstrap the approved directory
for Kilo. Without the change a sphinx warning about
the new spec rst file not being included anywhere causes the
build to fail. And applying the change with an empty approved
directory the pattern match fails and the build fails

Previously-approved: juno
Part of blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ib8b259f69c9072520acecba167b7b31707bcadaa

commit_message:
Allow reading a tenant router's external IP

Adds an external IPs field to the external gateway information
for a router so the external IP address of the router can be
read by the tenant.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1255142
Change-Id: If4e77c445e9b855ff77deea6c8df4a0b3cf249d4

commit_message:
Fix setup of Neutron core plugin in VPNaaS UT

One of the VPNaaS unit test setup routines creates
and extension manager but passes it a class but it
should be passing an instance of that class.

Change-Id: I589cdda0674fdf8fa20d92c2609e1ba6966125d8

commit_message:
Ensure sql upgrade tests can run with non-sqlite databases.

This patch fixes the issues that were preventing the running of
live sql upgrade tests (either by running test_sql_upgrade directly
or via test_sql_livetest), namely:

- Dropping the tables that were in existence before the current
  scope of migration in an order that is FK friendly
- Fixing an issue where the tables were being dropped in the
  wrong order in the downgrade of federation
- Ensuring we don't hold sessions open over upgrade/downgrade
  steps in our test methods

Limitations:

- This patch has not been tested with DB2

Closes-Bug: 1363047
Closes-Bug: 1375937
Change-Id: Ied4741a9646b57bc6f2ddcdc8a380ea55b2a9634

commit_message:
Add missing Disk unit to Overview Usage

Added unit to the Summary table and the csv report

Conflicts:

	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/overview/tests.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/projects/tests.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/overview/templates/overview/usage.csv

Change-Id: I91a0bdd13384098cd2e306413bfc103c99bbc418
Closes-Bug: #1346389
(cherry picked from commit https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109147/)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-01 17:17:10.000000000', 'message': "Save extended attributes when creating tar

The way redhat-common's extract-image script was creating the base
tarball caused file capabilities to get dropped, which meant that
things like ping in RHEL 7 images was unusable for regular users.
This change adds the necessary options to the tar call to maintain
as many extended attributes as possible.

bz reference: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1144149

Change-Id: Ibff99ce9bde01bc5ecf95dc3a5d3e2cebe5015b9
"}, {'created': '2014-10-02 22:08:04.000000000', 'message': "Save extended attributes when creating tar

The way redhat-common's extract-image script was creating the base
tarball caused file capabilities to get dropped, which meant that
things like ping in RHEL 7 images was unusable for regular users.
This change adds the necessary options to the tar call to maintain
as many extended attributes as possible.

permission problems in the resulting images.  Since that isn't
necessary to fix the ping issue it should be fine to drop those.

commit_message:
Save extended attributes when creating tar

The way redhat-common's extract-image script was creating the base
tarball caused file capabilities to get dropped, which meant that
things like ping in RHEL 7 images was unusable for regular users.
This change adds the necessary options to the tar call to maintain
as many extended attributes as possible.

--acls and --selinux are intentionally omitted, and the selinux
xattrs are filtered out because all of those items cause issues
in our chroot environment.  We restore selinux attributes at the
end of the build anyway so that shouldn't be a problem.

bz reference: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1144149

Change-Id: Ibff99ce9bde01bc5ecf95dc3a5d3e2cebe5015b9

commit_message:
Add admin tenant name to nova notifier

This change introduces the ability to use the nova admin
tenant name with the nova notifier in place of the nova
admin tenant id which may not be available when the neutron
service is being configured as is the case with tripleo
installations where the neutron service is configured and
started before the nova admin tenant has been configured in
keystone and thus does not have a known id.

DocImpact
Introduces the nova_admin_tenant_name configuration entry as
an optional configurable value in neutron.conf.  If the
nova_admin_tenant_name is configured and the nova_admin_tenanat_id
is not configured, a performance impact may be seen because
keystone will become involved in communication between neutron
and nova.

Change-Id: I33701d4dc9bf61595e44a49050c405ebca779091
Closes-Bug: #1331566

commit_message:
Retry getting the list of service plugins

On systems that start both neutron-server and neutron-l3-agent together,
there is a chance that the first call to neutron will timeout. Retry upto
4 more times to avoid the l3 agent exiting on startup.

This should make the l3 agent a little more robust on startup but still
not ideal, ideally it wouldn't exit and retry periodically.

Change-Id: I2171a164f3f77bccd89895d73c1c8d67f7190488
Closes-Bug: #1353953
Closes-Bug: #1368152
Closes-Bug: #1368795

commit_message:
nova-net: add more useful logging before raising FixedIpLimitExceeded

The OverQuota exception that we get back from the DB API contains some
useful information about the quota limits for the project and resource
and the current usage, so we can log that before raising
FixedIpLimitExceeded. Also logs the actual project ID passed to
quotas.reserve rather than context.project_id since it's possible those
are different.

This should help us figure out if we're leaking resources in gate runs.

Related-Bug: #1353962

Change-Id: Ia8a6d2336ddbbe28178be8d3ce4d97e6d4ab3787

commit_message:
Removing dependency on trove models in the guest agent

Reasons:
 - The guest agent is importing backup models and agent
   heartbeat, this triggers the all of the trove database
   setup logic which bloats the guest process on the host.

 - Moving the state to its own module and removing an unused
   function decreases the memory usage by about 15 - 20 megs.

Closes-Bug: #1375311
Change-Id: I126c0b89c170b325d85b3f09afca399b4f5de9e8

commit_message:
Fix a response header bug in the error middleware

Coerce the Content-Length of the custom error message to a string, not an
integer.  Some pure Python WSGI servers aren't strict and violate the WSGI
specification by automatically converting the value to a string.  Apache,
however, *is* strict, and considers this a 500 Internal Error

Fixes bug 1306963

Change-Id: I9b82ceee096b00c21c3b230dc67701bc40629968

[{'created': '2014-10-03 21:57:05.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Hard delete backup stack after successful update."

This reverts commit 7cf6e52cacd2382b44b9255e9a5ed13271841261.

This change appears to be the cause of many Tempest test breakages.  Prior
to this a new raw_template entry was created in the database after an
update, and the pointer to the new raw_template and the stack status were
changed atomically. Now those two pieces of data are being updated
separately... it seems like it is possible for Postgres to return the new
version of the stack on one call followed by the old version of the
template on another call. Tempest is observing the stack status change to
UPDATE_COMPLETE but then still getting data from the old template when
doing a resource list immediately after.

Change-Id: Ieea739bc45dcc365ccb6f09d0e848e310d327134

commit_message:
Revert "Hard delete backup stack after successful update."

This reverts commit 7cf6e52cacd2382b44b9255e9a5ed13271841261.

This change appears to be the cause of many Tempest test breakages.  Prior
to this a new raw_template entry was created in the database after an
update, and the pointer to the new raw_template and the stack status were
changed atomically. Now those two pieces of data are being updated
separately... it seems like it is possible for the database to return the
new version of the stack on one call followed by the old version of the
template on another call. Tempest is observing the stack status change to
UPDATE_COMPLETE but then still getting data from the old template when
doing a resource list immediately after.

Change-Id: Ieea739bc45dcc365ccb6f09d0e848e310d327134
Partial-Bug: #1370865

commit_message:
Trigger requirements run for requirements-py3.txt

The gate-.*requirements jobs are only triggered if certain files change.
Some projects have requirements-py3.txt or test-requirements-py3.txt.
Include as triggers all versions that the file update.py from the global
requirements repository handles.

Change-Id: Ib77229e7cc358059a6b3d6bcae0016959741db9d

commit_message:
Further coverage cleanup

Delete coverage jobs that are not setup properly at all, those that will
always fail. Examples are missing environments, missing scripts or
missing installed packages.

I did not delete jobs that were successfull but didn't collect any data
or those that failed for any reason.

Change-Id: I75299f7ef186bae4596ce2c6b5579b7e82813255

commit_message:
Increase timeout for sahara-buildimages

It's working not super fast right now, so, we need to increase
timeout for buidling images from defaults 30 minutes.

Change-Id: I485f8095ecd21b4c78a0ed23f2f23a1e072f2e97

commit_message:
Provide implementation to parse monitoring template in TOSCA library

The template deploys nodejs, nginx, monbodb, elasticsearch, logstash and
kibana as well collectd and rsyslog. The current patch covers nodejs and
mongodb.

Partially implements: blueprint enable-monitoring
Closes-Bug: #1369109

Change-Id: Ice602153c9b04ed11be48c6fec83fad8bda1c83a

commit_message:
Raise descriptive error for over volume quota

If you attempt to create a new instance booting from an image and you
were over your quota on cinder, the nova manager would see that as an
invalid block device. This raises a more descriptive error message in
the logs.

Closes-bug: #1013417
Change-Id: Ie50b97c31580da7fc38c6891d1f3646b91f8aa10
(cherry picked from commit 4711ff3adff2b4c9a54f5fb4448ace6558f82f6b)

commit_message:
Remove setUpClass added after cleanup

After the cleanup of setUpClass a new one managed to sneak
in. Removing it now, and enforcing the hacking rule in next
patchset.

Change-Id: If53b3a7d299f01f7c45739f5b2f023fbdb73aa45

commit_message:
Raise exception if ipv6 prefix is inappropriate for address mode

Address prefix to use with slaac and stateless ipv6 address modes
should be equal to 64 in order to work properly.
The patch adds corresponding validation and fixes unit tests
accordingly.

Change-Id: I6c344b21a69f85f2885a72377171f70309b26775
Closes-Bug: #1357084

commit_message:
Remove Resp status code checks in stress tests

As response code checks is done at client side,
tests case do not need to check the same again.

This patch removes status code checks in stress tests.
All removed status code checks are present on client side.

Partially Implements blueprint: client-checks-success

Change-Id: I1f09b25d6d6d1c966a0635509d670c55d9415468

[{'created': '2014-09-30 23:20:51.000000000', 'message': "Ensure sql upgrade tests can run with non-sqlite databases.

This patch fixes the issues that were preventing the running of
live sql upgrade tests (either by running test_sql_upgrade directly
or via test_sql_livetest), namely:

- Dropping the tables that were in existence before the current
  scope of migration in an order that is FK friendly
- Fixing an issue where the tables were being dropped in the
  wrong order in the downgrade of federation
- Ensuring we don't hold sessions open over upgrade/downgrade
  steps in our test methods

Limitations:

- This current version still does not work with Postgresql, due to
  an issue with exceptions not being raised/caught correctly in
  test_upgrade_region_unique_description(). This is being
  investigated
- This version has not been tested with DB2

Closes-Bug: 1363047
Closes-Bug: 1375937
Change-Id: Ied4741a9646b57bc6f2ddcdc8a380ea55b2a9634

commit_message:
Ensure sql upgrade tests can run with non-sqlite databases.

This patch fixes the issues that were preventing the running of
live sql upgrade tests (either by running test_sql_upgrade directly
or via test_sql_livetest), namely:

- Dropping the tables that were in existence before the current
  scope of migration in an order that is FK friendly
- Fixing an issue where the tables were being dropped in the
  wrong order in the downgrade of federation
- Ensuring we don't hold sessions open over upgrade/downgrade
  steps in our test methods

Limitations:

- This patch has not been tested with DB2

Closes-Bug: 1363047
Closes-Bug: 1375937
Change-Id: Ied4741a9646b57bc6f2ddcdc8a380ea55b2a9634

Maybe that is a point, we have a lot of specs in Juno and it seems hard to put all specs into right directories.

1) Submit a new blueprint with clear scope for Kilo, and submit a new spec also by keeping the existing spec in "implemented" directory.

commit_message:
Re-organize juno specs

As discussed at our nova meetings, reorganize the juno specs into
three directories:

 - proposed: things proposed which weren't approved
 - approved: things we approved but didn't implement
 - implemented: things approved and implemented

The first I suspect is the most controversial. I've done this
because I worry about the case where a future developer wants to
pick up something dropped by a previous developer, but has trouble
finding previous proposed specifications on the topic. Note that
the actual proposed specs for Juno are adding in a later commit.

Change-Id: Idcf55ca37a83d7098dcb7c2971240c4e8fd23dc8

commit_message:
Do not log password in swift URLs in g-registry

There was a debug level log with the locations added to it.
This change fixes the log to not contain that sensitive info.

Fixes bug 1348838

Conflicts:
	glance/registry/api/v1/images.py

Needed changes for Icehouse:
- use fixture.iteritems() instead of six.iteritems(fixture) in unit
  tests.

Change-Id: I3c5b29616c8d76bed17dbd31a8f4fc7ccd2dd945
(cherry picked from commit 28fdfdbaca81adcc94d5e6d57c55f7c985d6c512)

commit_message:
Skip certain tests that use migrate when it's not available

To move further toward py3.x support we need to skip certain
tests that currently will not work for py3.x due to the usage
of the migrate package (which still appears to not be/if ever
ready for py3.x)

Change-Id: I6f3a457e9d959cb6d208775c873547e78fafe210

commit_message:
Allows to specify disabled extension

This patch adds configuration options for disabling extensions
for the following services: compute, network, volume, and
object storage.

These new options will be used for skipping tests not only
according to enabled extensions, but also according to disabled
ones. This will simplify handling of situations where all
extensions except a few ones should be enabled.

Partially-implements: Blueprint branchless-tempest-extension

Change-Id: Ic9f13cb51166c0907002b20ac3229ddb25740702

"}, {'created': '2014-10-06 01:30:01.000000000', 'message': "fix issues with build-docker-image

- fix typo in --namespace option

    build-docker-image had a missing '$' in the code that handled the
    --namespace option.

- force builds to kollaglue namespace with 'latest' tag to use
  the --release flag

- build IMAGE after config and options processing to permit overriding
  PREFIX in .buildconf

commit_message:
fix issues with build-docker-image

- fix typo in --namespace option

    build-docker-image had a missing '$' in the code that handled the
    --namespace option.

- force builds to kollaglue namespace with 'latest' tag to use
  the --release flag

- build IMAGE after config and options processing to permit overriding
  PREFIX in .buildconf

Change-Id: Icf70b33080ef19643f133f2b6f60087c524bd4fb

commit_message:
Allow custom root labels

Makes the localboot element aware of the custom root fs labels
added in I596104d1a63b5dc6549e8460a1ae3da00165ef04 for
diskimage-builder.  That change must merge before this one.

Change-Id: Ic89379eca8699b27a4b89de9da3fc4f56011963e

commit_message:
Data source driver for ceilometer

The driver provides 3 lists :
1. Meters
2. Alarms
3. Events
The patch also includes test for the above lists.

Change-Id: Iab4f96fdf3f21ec6fab06f08aeaf3eb96bcf4d13

commit_message:
Break out quota refresh check code from quota_reserve()

This moves the logic that is checking if a quota refresh is needed into
a private method.

This is part of a larger series to refactor the quota_reserve method.

Partial-Bug: #1369605

Change-Id: I07fa1a5d53708f33b68a49186dbc5db15a1dbf17

commit_message:
Handle non-existent item when calling update_item

If update_item action(s) is(are) ADD and/or PUT, a new item
will be created if expected conditions are satisfied. Otherwise
ConditionalCheckFailedException will be thrown. If

commit_message:
Ironic: Do not try to unplug VIF if not associated

During instance spawn, Ironic attempts to unplug any plugged VIFs from
ports associated with an instance. If there are no associated VIFs
to unplug, this would raise an exeception that would be logged into
n-cpu. This patch fix that behavior by making the driver check if the
port has an VIF associated with it before trying to remove it.

Change-Id: I5608b9eec625452edda9a0c9eb366ece2a95800f
Closes-Bug: #1292733

commit_message:
Avoid usage of six.moves in local functions

Currently it appears that using six.moves in threaded code isn't
working as expected (something there in six does not appear to
be thread safe) so until this is fixed avoid using those moves
in functions in the examples and in the utility code (and instead
import the moved function at the top of the module in code to
avoid any threaded usage problems).

Upstream bug filed at:

https://bitbucket.org/gutworth/six/issue/98/

Fixes bug 1377514

Change-Id: I3fc1819df8fb42d0c3d394bbc7d047b09152af68

commit_message:
Fix the os_networks display to show cidr properly

Converting network_get and network_get_all to use objects broke
the display of the os_networks extension, because IPAddress
fields in Network objects are dumped as lists by the jsonutils
extension. We therefore must explicitly convert these object
field values to string.

The tests are updated to use objects so that we pick up bugs
like this in the future. Incorrect assertEqual parameter order
is fixed in the tests too since these are comparing dicts and
it's not fun debugging a MismatchError when the reference/actual
values are backwards.

Change-Id: I0f05a9b4d7bbe5fe0a3b110c191455ca7edefcb5
Closes-Bug: #1376945
Co-authored-by: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Fix schema definition admin_flavor_create

The api of flavor_create has a missing property level. Property "id"
is noneable and need to be excluded from negative testing.

Change-Id: I411eb8c29d0c00d6d64358ede26992ee2fe380c9
Closes-bug: #1375142

In the current state of the negative testing framework the import phase
consists in many complex operation during import phase. This fix reduces
the complexity during that phase to improve the performance,
debugability and robustness.

In this fix we only determine the test scenarios in the import phase. The
payloads are created while test execution. This also improves the
flexibility since the test executor has full access to the test variables.

Change-Id: I8deed33d37c5bf07c26118d6d66ada105d259c89

commit_message:
Reduce complexity during import phase

In the current state of the negative testing framework the import phase
consists in many complex operation during import phase. This fix reduces
the complexity during that phase to improve the performance,
debugability and robustness.

In this fix we only determine the test scenarios in the import phase. The
payloads are created while test execution. This also improves the
flexibility since the test executor has full access to the test variables.

Change-Id: I8deed33d37c5bf07c26118d6d66ada105d259c89
Partially-implements: bp autogen-negative-tests

commit_message:
Make glanceclient respect --public paremeter

In I66e82872988e3835e4f290f48dfc80538271426c we stopped respecting the
--public parameter but it is still available.

Fixes-bug: #1366808

Change-Id: I329dcfba7a5a4cef428c468f0c842561092a945a

Yes, the other review was dropped, but the comments I made on it have not been addressed here, so -1 still.'}, {'account_id': 12566, 'date': '2014-09-17 04:58:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Like Christopher Yeoh said: "something starting with '-' would be interpreted as an option rather than an argument unless specially quoted.", after investigation I have to agreed with this.
Kevin, if I put check in create_security_group method in v1(v3) shell module it will fail before get into that, because there will be not known argument (starting with -) through parser.
The other solution is to use "parse_known_args" method from parser but this involve many use cases, which also need to be validate (is that there is description, what if description starts with "-" as well). Do you think patch needs further work, or there is simplest solution ?
regards / Woody'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2014-09-17 16:25:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Honestly, I don't think there's a solution here that I'd be happy with; I really don't like the idea of special cases in novaclient/shell.py, especially such error prone ones: what if we needed to add an option to secgroup-create, as an example?  I also think that there's a limit to how much we can insulate a user from his own stupidity, and I feel like this might be just a bit beyond that; if we *can* with little effort, of course, it makes sense, but this is sounding like a lot of effort for little gain to me."}, {'account_id': 12566, 'date': '2014-10-06 18:09:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Friendly error message while creating security group

Validate parameter name before going to the parser, while
creating security group. Before that, there was an
error about no such parameter.
Now there is validation in case of:
* nova secgroup-create -name

Closes-Bug: #977192
Change-Id: Id10ebc7f720aa4183a6ed313388a7a006d17bc37

Remove identity and assignment kvs backends

As part of deprecating the kvs backends, this patch removes those
for identity and assignment.

Partially implements: bp removed-as-of-kilo

commit_message:
Adding a check to bandit for use of 'exec'

Python exec allows execution of strings as dynamic code. Possible
vector for code injection attack, but can also hide stuff from
other bandit checks when presented as a string.

Change-Id: Ic006c9913561283a9ef8d09098cbecc4c5871e22

The previous version checks if a value is equal to either True or False, if

and 1 to be converted to '0' and '1'.

commit_message:
Fix bug in value_to_congress

The previous version checks if a value is equal to either True or False, if
so, it converts the value to a string.  The problem is that 0 and 1 are equal
to False and True respectively in python which would cause integer values 0
and 1 to be converted to '0' and '1'.

This change uses isinstance(obj, bool) and does so before isinstance(obj, int)
because a bool value is also an instance of int.  Also, add a test to verify
this bug.

Change-Id: Ifbf17378c1ca660c47421b11a30204f9be1af056

commit_message:
Removed d6cage reload module warning messages

Previously, d6cage would log errors when the same module
was loaded more than once.

It is unclear whether this behavior is useful, and it
produced many errors during testing.  This change
logs a warning instead of an error when a module
is reloaded.

Closes-bug: 1360443
Change-Id: Id1add83b2fa8b7432ac5cc5d3156a13af92ba858

commit_message:
Document token hash algorithm option

With https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116509/ ,
django-openstack-auth will support a new option for the token hash
algorithm. This adds the documentation to Horizon's local settings
example file.

This is for security hardening. The token hash algorithm defaults
to MD5, which is considered too weak due to the potential for hash
collisions. Some security standards require a SHA2 hash algorithm to
be used.

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I6774b9b7215d191259586e4721e357487bb777cd
Closes-Bug: #1174499

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Allow cinder authtoken settings to be configurable

This patch is for allowing cafile, insecure,
memcached_servers, memcache_security_strategy,
memcache_secret_key and hash_algorithms to be
configurable.

Change-Id: If4e75092f969bb6b5df29d715e1cff696e41a9a3
Closes-Bug: #1370906

commit_message:
Add possibility to manage httpd service

puppet-horizon lacks of httpd service management. Unfortunately it is impossible
implement manage_service parameter as in other OpenStack related modules, so parameters
service_ensure and service_enable have been added.

Closes-bug: #1359823
Change-Id: I194d7caecbce5e527a14b9d69b7d76281b5bc680

commit_message:
Add a note regarding image properties for volumes

As introduced in Havana, the glance_core_properties option
in cinder is an important consideration if the core properties
of images are changed. This patch adds a note in the image metadata
section.

Change-Id: Icdc04c742349cfa9d6013dcb51b1f904e6fab391
Closes-Bug: 1329419

commit_message:
Fix exponentially growing AJAX updates for table rows

Schedule next table rows update only when the last row was updated.
Provide unit test for that regression with XHR and timeouts being
stubbed out via Sinon.js.

Change-Id: Id603a4fde5713d8f2b85b1dcf72c82c93a87c755
Closes-Bug: #1263665

Change-Id: I8320c789737ca6ca9fe04030a2c74c6fd6c303c8

commit_message:
add openssl to base image

we use openssl in many of our start scripts for password generation, so
openssl should probably be part of the base image.

Change-Id: I893adfa3b7d17249b6814fc161e6f3f1696d8cd6

commit_message:
Prepare for auth plugins

In order to get ready for auth plugins I kind of needed to
turn auth plugins on their head.  The goals:

* The plugin should know what to construct based on what the
  user provides.  If a token is provided, use it.
* If a token is provided and it expires, allow the user to reauth
  with user name and password without the user having to do
  anything special.
* Support auth plugin names like identity_v2 and identity_v3 where
  the user does not need to know exactly what method they are
  using.
* Keep is simple.

In the simple department, I think this makes it simplier for the
user.

Change-Id: I7778438930bad2a32f79189b46d4fe7dbfbb67f6

commit_message:
RabbitMQ heartbeat implementation

AMQP offers a heartbeat feature to ensure that the application layer
promptly finds out about disrupted connections (and also completely
unresponsive peers). If the client requests heartbeats on connection, rabbit
server will regularly send messages to each connections with the expectation of
a response.

Change-Id: I3dae1c1bee4ecf521903f3b1bee44dcda18bc3df
Co-Authored-By: Oleksii Zamiatin <ozamiatin@mirantis.com>
Related-Bug: #856764

Change-Id: I7cf746178f2a9fbcf6ee71a5cf083752f426664e

subject: Reset no_proxy when the node is installed behind a proxy
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-06 15:34:33.000000000', 'message': 'Reset no_proxy when the node is installed behind a proxy

Closes-Bug: 1291111
Closes-Bug: 1322200
Problem:
=======
When devstack is installed behind a proxy with proxy variables
http_proxy and https_proxy being exported and without exporting
no_proxy, the installation will fail. The reason is that any REST
request sent to Keystone will be redirected to the proxy server.
Solution:
========
Fix involves appending no_proxy variable with localhost,HOST_IP,
SERVICE_HOST if they are not included already and then exporting
the variable.
Save it into localrc.

Change-Id: I12693350b2e381eea83d00785f324db37966bb54
'}]
commit_message:
Reset no_proxy when the node is installed behind a proxy

Closes-Bug: 1291111
Closes-Bug: 1322200
Problem:
=======
When devstack is installed behind a proxy with proxy variables
http_proxy and https_proxy being exported and without exporting
no_proxy, the installation will fail. The reason is that any REST
request sent to Keystone will be redirected to the proxy server.
Solution:
========
Fix involves appending no_proxy variable with localhost,HOST_IP,
SERVICE_HOST if they are not included already and then exporting
the variable.
Save it into localrc.

Change-Id: I12693350b2e381eea83d00785f324db37966bb54

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-06 13:05:50.000000000', 'message': 'Supress error logs when exception is thrown

There are many cases when exceptions from the backend are expected and
these exceptions must not be logged as errors. For example it is a
common pattern to catch DuplicateName/AlreadyExists exceptions and
ignore them in the cases when multiple threads are trying to perform the
same operation. Currently there is no way for clients to prevent logging
these exceptions as errors and the proper way to fix this is to just
raise the exception in oslo and let the client decide if it must be
logged as an error or not.

Closes-Bug: #1377927
Change-Id: I5309cad5b0eeb380387eb3051d80c59b783561e8
'}]
commit_message:
Supress error logs when exception is thrown

There are many cases when exceptions from the backend are expected and
these exceptions must not be logged as errors. For example it is a
common pattern to catch DuplicateName/AlreadyExists exceptions and
ignore them in the cases when multiple threads are trying to perform the
same operation. Currently there is no way for clients to prevent logging
these exceptions as errors and the proper way to fix this is to just
raise the exception in oslo and let the client decide if it must be
logged as an error or not.

Closes-Bug: #1377927
Change-Id: I5309cad5b0eeb380387eb3051d80c59b783561e8

commit_message:
update vsm credential correctly

Today if we modify the n1kv VSM credential in the cisco_plugins.ini, the
older VSM ip address remains in the db, and all requests are sent to
the older VSM. This patch deletes all n1kv VSM credentials on neutron
start up before adding the newer VSM credentials. Hence making sure
that there is only one n1kv VSM IP address and credential in the db.

Change-Id: I772a86bf896a1d3d9c69c545ce6918b0fe3a2e48
Closes-Bug: #1341014
(cherry picked from commit 487b98a73f6be41697dd4f59a245f1a7f338a72f)

commit_message:
Remove font-awesome resources from muranodashboard/static

... because horizon packages them as xstatic package, muranodashboard
can get them as horizon static resources, no need to keep a separate
copy of them.

Change-Id: I53c2b0cf1ad19b7a805bb3a3b683f43d452083d4

commit_message:
Networks are not scheduled to DHCP agents for Cisco N1KV plugin

With the config option 'network_auto_schedule = False' in
neutron.conf, networks do not get scheduled to available DHCP
agents. The fix is to explicitly schedule the network as part
of the subnet creation flow.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/cisco/n1kv/test_n1kv_plugin.py

Change-Id: Id1f94a5844111a916f984d6dd7bda2cb4e11e1ee
Closes-Bug: #1356609
(cherry picked from commit 0fcedae747f257e2424b669ec65f32b76f12155a)

I get that, but you could just go with nil as the default value and an if statement around that value, that only adds it to the config if the attribute is not nil/false. This way it would not be in the config if md5 because thats the default, but would automatically be added if set to a value.'}, {'account_id': 6983, 'date': '2014-09-24 10:39:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Jan,
I prefer to config it explicitly.
1. current solution:
No matter 'md5' or other value, "OPENSTACK_TOKEN_HASH_ALGORITHM=YY" exists in the config file. It is explicit.
The use can easily know the current value via the config file.

2. your solution:
The user will have different user experiences on one option between 'md5' and other value.
if the attribute is not nil, "OPENSTACK_TOKEN_HASH_ALGORITHM=XX" (XX is not 'md5') exists in config file. It is explicit;
but if the attribute is nil, "OPENSTACK_TOKEN_HASH_ALGORITHM=md5" does not exist in config file. 
The user has to go into the document or the source code to understand what the current value is.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-24 12:56:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified-1

Minor inline comment.   And I would agree that in most cases we have been putting in the base openstack default instead of using nil and if/check.   While this means we have to make changes when ever the base changes default, that's been very rare for a release boundary.   

Ideally I would like to see Chef step up support for better attribute/template integration so this could be cleaner and automatic.
- no section support (in resource or specs)
- no clean way to avoid the ugly if checking for nil attributes
- no way to autogen template from attribute metadata, avoids writing many lines of code, just describe the attribute properly."}, {'account_id': 6983, 'date': '2014-09-25 05:11:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-25 06:12:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified-1

[{'created': '2014-09-25 08:51:20.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I1a0836c12fee97a5192aa40f5c2948809d009ae9
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I1a0836c12fee97a5192aa40f5c2948809d009ae9
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Refactor stack actions and add stack check

All stack actions are very similar and can reuse the same code.  This
also adds an entry for stack-check as well.

Change-Id: I111d1af8a17e9fc30c5f52a26041a6912f1e4625
Implements: blueprint stack-check

commit_message:
libvirt: convert volume snapshot test case to avoid DB usage

Convert the LibvirtVolumeSnapshotTestCase so that it avoids
creating instance objects in the database. This allows it to
be converted to use NoDBTestCase improving perf from 4.2s
to 2.3s

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: Idf4d29a0df2280c78fe879fa09632c666ff04436

commit_message:
libvirt: convert volume usage test case to avoid DB usage

Convert LibvirtVolumeUsageTestCase so that it avoids creating an
instance in the database. This allows it to be switched over to
use NoDBTestCase, improving perf from 1.7s to 0.13s.

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: If2ab915388c2a1ba0565d4aa8bb66b98db535094

subject: libvirt: convert LibvirtNonblockingTestCase to avoid DB usage

commit_message:
libvirt: convert LibvirtNonblockingTestCase to avoid DB usage

The LibvirtNonblockingTestCase test case does not do anything DB
related. Convert it to NoDBTestCase to avoid DB setup penalty.
This improves perf from 1.8s to 0.4s

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: I6ff4f46a2e8c2e436d40dd47134f5ec496ce153f

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-04 18:51:57.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
libvirt: convert firewall tests to avoid DB usage

The test_firewall.py test suite had alot of code which created
and accessed database objects. This can all be avoided by making
more use of mock to patch out a handful of object access functions.
The test_cidr_rule_nwfilter_xml was deleted entirely since it was
never actually validating any aspect of the nwfilter execution,
so didn't add any benefits over the other test functions that
run.

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: I7172edace9e568d961fc1dc9f449cd858551bb0d
